1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:27,960
 The movement from self-certainty to perception, you know, it's like, I get it.

2
00:00:27,960 --> 00:00:37,140
 I mean, it makes sense. I understand. I mean, for me, I had a number of thoughts and notes that I jotted down, not least of which is nobody talks very much.

3
00:00:37,180 --> 00:00:52,020
 There must have been like a huge mine filled with semicolons somewhere in the Yenna region because this book, the number of semicolons per page is like nothing I've ever seen.

4
00:00:52,920 --> 00:01:07,260
 Yeah. No, the syntax is so strange. And I don't bizarre. It's not it's not secondary. I mean, that's something I think I will continuously come back to is kind of part of my thesis on Hagel.

5
00:01:07,260 --> 00:01:14,480
 Like the syntax is what gives the dialectic its life. Like it's not some accessory to the text.

6
00:01:15,160 --> 00:01:26,500
 So you should read Dan Smith, who used to be here. He's now well, he's out of academia now down in Texas. He wrote, I think, an excellent piece. It's called like bad writing.

7
00:01:27,380 --> 00:01:39,060
 If you text me, you know, I'll forget. But if you text or email me, I'll remember and find the site for you. But his claim there is that the movement of Hagel, he uses Hagel, Adorno, and I think Zizek.

8
00:01:39,680 --> 00:01:47,880
 And he's like, it's negative dialectic, whatever. But the claim is precisely what you're saying, which is the syntax is the pedagogy.

9
00:01:48,420 --> 00:01:48,600
 Right.

10
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:53,860
 You know, so it's just a site that you can use. And it's a smart article. It's Dan. He's a smart guy.

11
00:01:54,300 --> 00:01:57,200
 Yeah. No, I'll have to. I'll write it down. Dan Smith.

12
00:01:57,320 --> 00:01:57,480
 Yeah.

13
00:01:57,580 --> 00:02:16,740
 Yeah. Dan Smith. And the title of it is like bad writing. He's taking people that have conventionally been considered bad writers. And he's saying it's only bad writing in the sense of some romantic experience of reading. It's not bad writing in the sense of a pedagogy.

14
00:02:17,140 --> 00:02:17,260
 Right.

15
00:02:17,260 --> 00:02:19,400
 And that those are different kinds of things, you know.

16
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:27,780
 So, yeah, it's Hagel, Adorno. And I really feel like the third is Zizek, the third example he takes, but I'm not sure.

17
00:02:28,620 --> 00:02:31,120
 Could it be Butler with the bad writing awards?

18
00:02:31,900 --> 00:02:34,900
 It could have been Butler. You might be right. It could have been.

19
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:37,460
 Yeah, she's always talked about with that conversation.

20
00:02:38,360 --> 00:02:41,840
 Yeah, but that's a different, I mean, that circumstance was so political.

21
00:02:42,820 --> 00:02:42,980
 Yeah.

22
00:02:43,640 --> 00:02:49,660
 I mean, implicitly. So a lot of people don't. Like Chris Holcomb wrote and published an essay on this and never really knew.

23
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:55,620
 Because when he showed it to me and I was like, Chris, you completely ignore the politics of this journal.

24
00:02:55,780 --> 00:03:00,720
 Like it's a journal that gave her that award and it's an analytic, it's a conservative analytic journal.

25
00:03:01,540 --> 00:03:05,360
 And if you look at the winners, they're all continental, you know, continental philosophers.

26
00:03:05,820 --> 00:03:11,500
 Well, it's funny to me, like reading this and then going to Butler and being like, she's too confusing.

27
00:03:12,160 --> 00:03:22,920
 Like, yeah, but Butler is like, like very clear and like there's an emphasis on clarity and simplicity when you look at someone like Hegel or someone like Deleuze.

28
00:03:23,020 --> 00:03:27,620
 Like, you know what I mean? Like what? I've never had the sensation that Butler was difficult to read.

29
00:03:28,420 --> 00:03:28,520
 Yeah.

30
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:28,960
 Me neither.

31
00:03:29,340 --> 00:03:29,540
 Agree.

32
00:03:30,020 --> 00:03:30,580
 Yeah.

33
00:03:30,940 --> 00:03:31,580
 Agree with you.

34
00:03:31,800 --> 00:03:36,740
 I mean, not in any way, not in any sense that any philosophy is difficult to read.

35
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:37,220
 Right.

36
00:03:37,560 --> 00:03:38,200
 Right, right, right.

37
00:03:39,100 --> 00:03:39,320
 Right.

38
00:03:39,660 --> 00:03:45,460
 And unfortunately, but unfortunately she wrote that, the same has been true whenever I teach that in grad classes.

39
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:49,680
 Grad students across the board are always like, why do people think this is so hard to read?

40
00:03:49,780 --> 00:03:52,100
 Like, this doesn't seem that hard to read.

41
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:53,820
 I mean, it's philosophy, you know.

42
00:03:54,220 --> 00:04:00,600
 But unfortunately she wrote that, she wrote a defense after, this is a couple years after, after getting that award.

43
00:04:00,680 --> 00:04:07,980
 She wrote a defense that was published in the New York Times and her defense was difficult ideas require difficult writing, which is the worst.

44
00:04:08,940 --> 00:04:10,600
 I mean, to me, it's the worst defense.

45
00:04:10,780 --> 00:04:15,100
 Like, the proper defense is this is not difficult writing for people who read philosophy.

46
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:16,520
 Right, yeah.

47
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:17,880
 She should have just done that take.

48
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:19,560
 Yeah, that would have been a more modest take.

49
00:04:20,360 --> 00:04:21,040
 Right, right.

50
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:33,020
 Well, because what she does is she links the ideas to the quality of the writing and that's a whole representational argument that shouldn't, she shouldn't, you wouldn't think that she would be supportive.

51
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:34,340
 That's right.

52
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:41,620
 I regret, I mean, it's so much because so many times I've heard people reference Butler's defense and I'm like, oh, I hate that defense so much.

53
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:49,440
 There's a really good one, which is, this is a specialist idiom like every other specialist idiom in the world.

54
00:04:50,100 --> 00:04:50,140
 Right.

55
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:56,160
 And for that specialist idiom, it's not to, like, mathematics is bad writing, right?

56
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:58,960
 Because it's not written for us to understand.

57
00:04:59,100 --> 00:05:01,000
 Like, quantum mechanics, bad writing.

58
00:05:01,240 --> 00:05:01,440
 Yeah.

59
00:05:01,540 --> 00:05:09,060
 Nobody says quantum mechanics is bad writing because they understand it's a specialist language, an idiom for physicists.

60
00:05:10,180 --> 00:05:16,200
 Yeah, it's a technical language and insofar as Butler's is a technical language, it's pretty simple.

61
00:05:16,640 --> 00:05:27,460
 It's symmetrical, it's not, like, it's not even that ambiguous when you, like, if you compare it to Hegel or a lot of these writers that we're, that we're dealing with, you know?

62
00:05:27,780 --> 00:05:28,040
 Yeah.

63
00:05:29,280 --> 00:05:29,680
 Yeah.

64
00:05:29,820 --> 00:05:35,400
 Although, interestingly, people don't really say that about Deleuze, even though Deleuze is way harder to read.

65
00:05:35,860 --> 00:05:48,140
 But because it's so clearly making, you know, neologism, you know, because it's so clearly kind of playful, for whatever reason, people just don't associate that with bad writing.

66
00:05:48,260 --> 00:05:53,800
 And they just, like, oh, well, they're being playful, they're just making up bodybuildings and, right, they're creative, right, right.

67
00:05:54,140 --> 00:05:54,260
 Yeah.

68
00:05:55,120 --> 00:06:05,840
 But I have a strain, I mean, I'm still, my reading and relationship with Butler has sort of evolved over the last few years and she's still pretty central to my project.

69
00:06:06,340 --> 00:06:15,920
 But if you read any of, like, her most recent stuff, it seems like she's kind of regressed into just a basic liberal humanism.

70
00:06:16,420 --> 00:06:27,360
 Like, and I know there's, there's a difference between pop butler and, like, hard theoretical butler, but the pop butler is not good for me.

71
00:06:27,780 --> 00:06:37,180
 Like, she's published a couple pieces in just, like, popular magazines recently and it's like, these are just strange, like, really conservative arguments, you know?

72
00:06:37,280 --> 00:06:37,500
 Yeah.

73
00:06:37,580 --> 00:06:38,780
 I don't know if you've read any of them.

74
00:06:38,980 --> 00:06:40,080
 It's hard to imagine.

75
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:40,800
 I have.

76
00:06:41,140 --> 00:06:42,860
 I've had the same response that you did.

77
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:45,080
 It's like, this sounds like liberalism to me.

78
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:45,520
 Yeah.

79
00:06:45,520 --> 00:06:50,040
 The only thing that I give her a break for, well, there are many things I give her a break for because I think she's smart as fuck.

80
00:06:50,240 --> 00:06:57,080
 But, like, being in a position like she is is something that I will never understand, which is I have to write, right?

81
00:06:57,120 --> 00:06:59,500
 I get to write for you guys, right?

82
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:06,520
 And for a fairly narrow group of, you know, of sort of theory types in the rhetoric field or whatever.

83
00:07:06,660 --> 00:07:09,300
 And maybe there's a few outliers in philosophy or whatever.

84
00:07:09,300 --> 00:07:18,780
 But, like, I don't ever have to be concerned that the bulk of the people responding to my thing are going to say, make it intelligible to me, you know?

85
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:19,140
 Right.

86
00:07:19,220 --> 00:07:20,220
 And she really is.

87
00:07:20,280 --> 00:07:25,900
 I mean, she is a – she's more of a public figure than sort of intellectual anymore.

88
00:07:26,020 --> 00:07:27,820
 And I don't mean that as a disparaging comment.

89
00:07:27,960 --> 00:07:39,800
 It's because of her extraordinary success that she's called on and asked to speak to, you know, the Palestinian question at MLA, for example, a couple of years ago, right, when there was that.

90
00:07:40,220 --> 00:07:43,580
 And she is called upon to offer a perspective.

91
00:07:43,820 --> 00:07:57,740
 Well, you know, she can't possibly be a master of all of this content and also speak to all of these constituencies in that sort of – you know, Derrida, you know, there's Derrida that's like that as well.

92
00:07:57,740 --> 00:08:06,940
 You know, there are times where, like, talking on apartheid and he usually managed to turn it back to some sort of esoteric question of hospitality and et cetera, et cetera.

93
00:08:07,120 --> 00:08:17,240
 But there are moments where I'm like, yeah, I just can't understand the position that a person like that has gone from this and now they've got a – we call it a larger public.

94
00:08:17,360 --> 00:08:19,900
 But it's just a different – it's a different public.

95
00:08:20,920 --> 00:08:23,740
 And to write, it's like I don't –

96
00:08:23,740 --> 00:08:31,620
 Yeah, well, you assume a political position and then your views sort of by necessity have to be narrowed in a way, you know.

97
00:08:31,620 --> 00:08:42,040
 I mean, her defense of academia in that one article – I forget what the publication was – it was like this makes perfect sense if you're speaking from her position.

98
00:08:42,840 --> 00:08:43,500
 Right, right.

99
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:52,880
 So, but from anybody – from my position, from your guys' position, it's like that argument, it was so elitist, which whatever, there's good and bad versions of every writer.

100
00:08:53,380 --> 00:08:56,000
 So, it's like, well, I guess this is just the version I don't like.

101
00:08:56,420 --> 00:08:57,120
 I mean, you know what I mean?

102
00:08:57,180 --> 00:08:58,260
 So, I don't know.

103
00:08:58,380 --> 00:08:59,220
 It's kind of arbitrary.

104
00:08:59,420 --> 00:08:59,600
 Right.

105
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:00,100
 Maybe.

106
00:09:00,300 --> 00:09:00,540
 Yeah.

107
00:09:01,840 --> 00:09:02,400
 But, yeah.

108
00:09:02,540 --> 00:09:16,260
 And she – and I think – I mean, look, the other thing to keep in mind is how totally excoriated she was by so many feminists back in the 80s – well, rather, the 90s, late 80s and early 90s because of her stuff was unreadable.

109
00:09:16,260 --> 00:09:18,920
 And that she was not supporting the cause.

110
00:09:18,920 --> 00:09:21,500
 And my take on that was that bothered her, right?

111
00:09:21,640 --> 00:09:27,240
 Like, because she very much saw herself as an activist, activist theorist.

112
00:09:28,220 --> 00:09:38,240
 And so, yeah, it does seem like her work became more recognizably activist rather than recognizably – I mean, she's still smart as fuck, like, obviously.

113
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:45,500
 But it just seems – and, again, that's a circumstance where I can't imagine it, you know?

114
00:09:45,980 --> 00:09:47,820
 I think that – that's my sense, too.

115
00:09:47,940 --> 00:09:59,960
 I mean, think about the sort of genealogy and series of critiques she gives at the beginning of Gender Trouble where, I mean, it's not just that, you know, she's got shit for being, you know, quote, unquote, unreadable.

116
00:09:59,960 --> 00:10:09,000
 But she also, like, really went after a whole bunch of, you know, concepts that are pretty central to most versions of feminism.

117
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:13,820
 Like, there is a recognizable thing that we can call woman, right?

118
00:10:14,040 --> 00:10:14,360
 Right.

119
00:10:14,780 --> 00:10:24,060
 Which, to me, I mean, that makes Butler far more interesting as a – I mean, as a feminist to actually take up, you know, woman – the category of woman as a question.

120
00:10:24,060 --> 00:10:37,060
 And to question the – I mean, to my mind, you know, like, her and de Beauvoir are, you know, at the – you know, are the most interesting thinkers in that arena.

121
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:55,920
 But someone like Siksou, who just sort of, like, assumes sort of, like, prefigured versions of masculinity and femininity and then ascribes them to kinds of writing, is just like, you know, you're not actually thinking about gender.

122
00:10:56,060 --> 00:11:03,060
 You're just thinking about the way that contemporary gender norms get distributed and pointing out very obvious disparities between them.

123
00:11:03,100 --> 00:11:04,680
 But you're not thinking about gender at all.

124
00:11:04,680 --> 00:11:09,420
 I mean, that's a – that's the tough part.

125
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:10,200
 Yeah.

126
00:11:10,420 --> 00:11:24,440
 What seems to suck is that, like, the more activist, like, the bent of your writing becomes or the more – like, if you have dogs in a fight, the less adventurous and provocative your thinking becomes.

127
00:11:24,700 --> 00:11:27,120
 Which doesn't seem like it has to be the case.

128
00:11:27,160 --> 00:11:30,200
 It just seems like that's usually the way it goes, you know.

129
00:11:30,560 --> 00:11:46,360
 Which it's like someone like Zizek, he will have, like, kind of activist political tendencies, but the writing itself doesn't seem to be burdened by, like, a responsibility to humanity or to a specific group, you know.

130
00:11:46,360 --> 00:12:01,480
 Which I find that uncomfortable sometimes reading him, but I also – I don't think I could ever, like, fully just endorse something, which is what Butler seems to lean into later in her career, you know, that kind of orientation.

131
00:12:01,900 --> 00:12:02,380
 I don't know.

132
00:12:02,660 --> 00:12:13,500
 I mean, it seems like you could find a balance between those two, but for me, the more explicitly, like, about social justice issues you become, the less adventurous the thinking.

133
00:12:14,040 --> 00:12:14,700
 I don't know.

134
00:12:14,800 --> 00:12:15,480
 It's just – yeah.

135
00:12:16,360 --> 00:12:23,320
 Well, you have to harden yourself into a position to advocate for something generally means you have to articulate the boundaries of the thing that you're advocating for, right?

136
00:12:23,440 --> 00:12:23,640
 Right.

137
00:12:23,880 --> 00:12:24,240
 Yeah, exactly.

138
00:12:24,760 --> 00:12:39,000
 And I've always felt like – and this is just in the microcosm that is the classroom, but particularly for undergrads, but I've always felt like current events, like, I felt a responsibility to say something interesting about them.

139
00:12:39,160 --> 00:12:47,740
 And I often don't have anything interesting to say, and I feel like that, like – and that's a much, much smaller microcosm.

140
00:12:47,740 --> 00:13:00,280
 I imagine, you know, projecting that to the position of, like, you know, Judith Butler or Zizek or someone who, you know, where anything that they write on a topic – and they're being asked constantly, like, hey, will you write about this issue?

141
00:13:00,360 --> 00:13:02,100
 Will you write about – will you do something on this issue?

142
00:13:02,220 --> 00:13:05,760
 Will you come give a talk on this, you know, to this group or whatever?

143
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:10,600
 And I can't – I can't imagine that sort of success.

144
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:11,700
 I think that you're right.

145
00:13:11,780 --> 00:13:20,200
 It would just sort of like, well, now I've got to have something interesting to say about something that's, like I said, a current event where I'm like, well, things happened and other things happened.

146
00:13:20,820 --> 00:13:25,600
 Well, some stuff – I mean, have you read really anything interesting about the pandemic?

147
00:13:25,900 --> 00:13:30,860
 Like, literally, over the past year, have you read anything that was like, wow, that's really interesting and provocative?

148
00:13:30,860 --> 00:13:31,780
 Oh, bylines give it away.

149
00:13:31,860 --> 00:13:33,400
 There's nothing to read beyond the byline.

150
00:13:34,240 --> 00:13:34,940
 Yeah, yeah.

151
00:13:35,660 --> 00:13:36,660
 I don't know, man.

152
00:13:36,780 --> 00:13:40,140
 There was this brilliant essay in this PNR special issue.

153
00:13:40,660 --> 00:13:41,620
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

154
00:13:42,440 --> 00:13:44,100
 By this Wuckelbauer guy.

155
00:13:44,140 --> 00:13:44,840
 Right, right, right.

156
00:13:45,880 --> 00:13:46,920
 You had to write it.

157
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:47,760
 You had to write it.

158
00:13:47,880 --> 00:13:48,880
 You didn't read anything.

159
00:13:48,920 --> 00:13:49,500
 You had to write it.

160
00:13:49,500 --> 00:13:50,460
 I had to write it.

161
00:13:50,560 --> 00:13:50,700
 Yeah.

162
00:13:52,040 --> 00:13:55,220
 You know, and it's actually – it's about styles of reading, right?

163
00:13:55,280 --> 00:14:00,860
 And that's what it ended up being about is how to resist the rage response of resentment.

164
00:14:01,220 --> 00:14:02,440
 I mean, that's what it was about.

165
00:14:02,440 --> 00:14:05,660
 And the interesting thing was I went through – I didn't read all of the other ones.

166
00:14:06,040 --> 00:14:09,880
 I read just a few from some of the folks that I know, and they were all rage responses.

167
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:11,920
 They were all angry.

168
00:14:12,140 --> 00:14:14,500
 And I was like, wow, that's an interesting juxtaposition.

169
00:14:14,680 --> 00:14:22,800
 I wonder – because, you know, in my typical cryptic way, I don't say, like, hey, we need to resist the rage response, and here's a possible way of doing it.

170
00:14:22,800 --> 00:14:30,340
 I just sort of start with, here's rage, I want to do something else, you know, so it's like it can easily not be seen as in dialogue with them.

171
00:14:30,580 --> 00:14:30,840
 But, yeah.

172
00:14:31,220 --> 00:14:31,400
 Right.

173
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:36,420
 How to do – I mean, to me, thinking is, like, it's hard, right?

174
00:14:36,620 --> 00:14:38,340
 And it's particularly when you're pissed.

175
00:14:38,440 --> 00:14:43,140
 Or, in my case, in the last couple of months, especially last week, when I'm worried or stressed.

176
00:14:43,380 --> 00:14:46,060
 Like, thinking is not something I can do.

177
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:51,980
 I mean, it's just – and, again, I mean, I don't mean, like, can I manage to deal with my life, of course.

178
00:14:52,400 --> 00:14:56,800
 But can I, like, do anything that makes me go, huh, that's an interesting direction.

179
00:14:56,880 --> 00:14:57,660
 I'd like to pursue that.

180
00:14:57,740 --> 00:14:58,460
 I can't.

181
00:15:02,940 --> 00:15:19,680
 This is why I, by the way, I love teaching that section in book two of the rhetoric on the emotions and the way that Aristotle sort of, like, diagnoses, you know, what I would call, like, a physics of affective dynamics.

182
00:15:20,240 --> 00:15:24,280
 They're, like, you know, what does anger do?

183
00:15:24,360 --> 00:15:27,860
 It takes up an object as the object of its anger.

184
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:29,460
 It has to draw boundaries around.

185
00:15:29,580 --> 00:15:31,160
 It has to create a rationale.

186
00:15:31,400 --> 00:15:35,440
 It has to create sort of, like, a harm done to something, right?

187
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:38,740
 And, you know, it tightens your focus.

188
00:15:38,880 --> 00:15:42,840
 It makes all of the boundaries look that much more concrete.

189
00:15:42,840 --> 00:15:50,140
 And it opens up avenues for quicker, more decisive, more powerful action.

190
00:15:50,660 --> 00:15:54,960
 But, by God, does it shut down the capacity to think and be curious about something, right?

191
00:15:54,960 --> 00:15:55,260
 It does.

192
00:15:55,260 --> 00:15:57,180
 It does for me, for damn sure.

193
00:15:57,760 --> 00:15:57,920
 Yeah.

194
00:15:58,680 --> 00:16:05,780
 I just like thinking about emotions in that way and less about the qualitative, you know, like, what's it like to be this?

195
00:16:05,780 --> 00:16:21,160
 It's like, no, like, how does this situation, how does, you know, what this thing that we call, you know, sadness or fear or whatever else, how is it really much more of, like, you know, a set of relationships and a set of stylistic relationships to others?

196
00:16:21,160 --> 00:16:30,260
 Well, and then anger is more comforting because it takes an object, like you said.

197
00:16:30,620 --> 00:16:44,880
 Like, without an object, it becomes just sort of a flat depression or existential angst, you know, and that's the much more uncomfortable state because there's no distinct object to pin, you know, to pin down.

198
00:16:45,820 --> 00:17:01,840
 Well, and look, that's, frankly, that's a perfectly good description of what the Trump political sphere did quite well is it took this amorphous ennui of, you know, working class America and said liberals, you know, and like, fuck the liberals, let's piss them off.

